AI CA5 Phase2 Report¶

Atieh Armin - 810197648¶

The goal of this project is to get familiar with Keras library and implement a neural network that identifies COVID19 or PNEUMONIA using Keras.

Preprocessing¶

First, the train data and the test data are read using flow_from_directory function. The target size of the images are set to (80,80), the color mode is set to grayscale and the batch size is 32.

from google.colab import drive
drive.mount('/content/drive')

In [4]:
from tensorflow.keras import *
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.image as mpimg
import numpy as np
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report

def get_labels(loader):
  labels = []
  for i in range(len(loader)):
    x_batch,y_batch = loader.next()
    for label in y_batch:
      labels.append(backend.argmax(label))
  return np.array(labels)

def print_details(history,train_data,test_data):
  predictions = ANN.predict(train_data)
  labels = get_labels(train_data)
  classification_report(labels,backend.argmax(predictions).numpy())

  predictions = ANN.predict(test_data)
  labels = get_labels(test_data)
  classification_report(labels,backend.argmax(predictions).numpy())

  plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
  plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
  plt.title('Model Loss')
  plt.ylabel('Loss')
  plt.xlabel('Epoch')
  plt.legend(['train','test'], loc='upper left')
  plt.show()

def data_reset(scale):
  dataLoader = preprocessing.image.ImageDataGenerator(rescale=scale)
  train_data = dataLoader.flow_from_directory("/content/Data/train",
                                             target_size = (80,80),
                                             color_mode = "grayscale",
                                             batch_size = 32)
  test_data = dataLoader.flow_from_directory("/content/Data/test",
                                             target_size = (80,80),
                                             color_mode = "grayscale",
                                             batch_size = 32)
  return train_data,test_data

Implementing Neural Network¶

A neural network with two hidden layers is implemented with the parameters shown below:

  1. Activation function of hidden layers = Relu
  2. Activation function of output layer = Softmax
  3. Number of the neurons of the hidden layers = 1024
  4. Batch size = 32
  5. Epochs = 10
  6. Loss function = Crossentropy
In [46]:
inp = layers.Input(shape=(80,80,1))
first_layer = layers.Flatten()(inp)
second_layer = layers.Dense(1024,activation="relu")(first_layer)
third_layer = layers.Dense(1024,activation="relu")(second_layer)
output_layer = layers.Dense(3,activation="softmax")(third_layer)
ANN = models.Model(inputs = inp,outputs = output_layer)
ANN.compile(optimizer=optimizers.SGD(learning_rate=0.01),loss="categorical_crossentropy",metrics=["accuracy"])

The summary of the network is shown below.

Now lets see another neural network which the activation function of its hidden layer is Tanh. As shown bellow the loss value is not nan anymore and the accuracy is better. This happend becaues tanh automatically returns an output in range (-1,1). Thus, weights and outputs of the layer is in a range and the network won't overflow. The general solution for this problem is to normalize numbers before get them as inputs. This is done in the next section by dividing numbers by 255.

In [50]:
train_data, test_data = data_reset(None)

inp = layers.Input(shape=(80,80,1))
first_layer = layers.Flatten()(inp)
second_layer = layers.Dense(1024,activation="tanh")(first_layer)
third_layer = layers.Dense(1024,activation="tanh")(second_layer)
output_layer = layers.Dense(3,activation="softmax")(third_layer)
ANN = models.Model(inputs = inp,outputs = output_layer)
ANN.compile(optimizer=optimizers.SGD(learning_rate=0.01),loss="categorical_crossentropy",metrics=["accuracy"])

inp = layers.Input(shape=(80,80,1))

Optimizers¶

SGD with Momentum¶

A major disadvantage of the Mini Batch SGD algorithm is that updates of weight are very noisy. SGD with momentum overcomes this disadvantage by denoising the gradients. Updates of weight are dependent on noisy derivative and if we somehow denoise the derivatives then converging time will decrease. The idea is to denoise derivative using exponential weighting average that is to give more weightage to recent updates compared to the previous update. Momentum at time ‘t’ is computed using all previous updates giving more weightage to recent updates compared to the previous update. This lead to speed up the convergence. Momentum has 2 advantages which makes it a better choice than SGD:

  1. Reduces the oscillations and high variance of the parameters.

  2. Converges faster than gradient descent.

Here is the implementation of the last neural network with different momentum:

1) Mumentum = 0.5

In [57]:
train_data, test_data = data_reset(1/255.)

inp = layers.Input(shape=(80,80,1))
first_layer = layers.Flatten()(inp)
second_layer = layers.Dense(4096,activation="relu")(first_layer)
third_layer = layers.Dense(2048,activation="relu")(second_layer)
fourth_layer = layers.Dense(1024,activation="relu")(third_layer)
output_layer = layers.Dense(3,activation="softmax")(fourth_layer)

ANN = models.Model(inputs = inp,outputs = output_layer)

ANN.compile(optimizer=optimizers.SGD(learning_rate=0.01,momentum=0.5) ,loss="categorical_crossentropy",metrics=["accuracy"])

Adam¶

Adam (Adaptive Moment Estimation) works with momentums of first and second order. The intuition behind the Adam is that we don’t want to roll so fast just because we can jump over the minimum, we want to decrease the velocity a little bit for a careful search.

Epochs¶

We are using a limited dataset and to optimise the learning and the graph we are using Adam. So, updating the weights with single pass or one epoch is not enough. As the number of epochs increases, more number of times the weight are changed in the neural network and the curve goes from underfitting to optimal to overfitting curve.

Ways to prevent overfitting: One of the first methods we should try when we need to reduce overfitting is regularisation. It involves adding an extra element to the loss function, which punishes our model for being too complex or, in simple words, for using too high values in the weight matrix. This way we try to limit its flexibility, but also encourage it to build solutions based on multiple features. Two popular versions of this method are L1 - Least Absolute Deviations (LAD) and L2 - Least Square Errors (LS). Equations describing these regularisations are given below. In most cases the use of L1 is preferable, because it reduces the weight values of less important features to zero, very often eliminating them completely from the calculations. In a way, it is a built-in mechanism for automatic featur selection. Moreover, L2 does not perform very well on datasets with a large number of outliers.

Lets train the neural network for 20 epochs.

Loss Functions¶

You saw the results of neural networks with CrossEntropy Loss function before.

Here is the neural network with MSE loss function. MSE does not give good result for classifications. There are two reasons why Mean Squared Error(MSE) is a bad choice for binary classification problems:

  • First, using MSE means that we assume that the underlying data has been generated from a normal distribution (a bell-shaped curve). In Bayesian terms this means we assume a Gaussian prior. While in reality, a dataset that can be classified into two categories (i.e binary) is not from a normal distribution but a Bernoulli distribution. If we use maximum likelihood estimation(MLE), assuming that the data is from a normal distribution(a wrong assumption, by the way), we get the MSE as a Cost function for optimizing our model.
  • Secondly, the MSE function is non-convex for binary classification. In simple terms, if a binary classification model is trained with MSE Cost function, it is not guaranteed to minimize the Cost function. This is because MSE function expects real-valued inputs in range(-∞, ∞), while binary classification models output probabilities in range(0,1) through the sigmoid/logistic function.
In [5]:
train_data, test_data = data_reset(1/255.)

first_layer = layers.Flatten()(inp)

Regularization¶

This technique discourages learning a more complex or flexible model, so as to avoid the risk of overfitting. There are mainly two types of regularization techniques:

  • L1 regularization or LASSO regression.
  • L2 regularization or Ridge regression.
In [7]:
train_data, test_data = data_reset(1/255.)

inp = layers.Input(shape=(80,80,1))
first_layer = layers.Flatten()(inp)
second_layer = layers.Dense(4096,activation="relu",kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.0001))(first_layer)
third_layer = layers.Dense(2048,activation="relu",kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.0001))(second_layer)
fourth_layer = layers.Dense(1024,activation="relu",kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.0001))(third_layer)
output_layer = layers.Dense(3,activation="softmax",kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.0001))(fourth_layer)

ANN = models.Model(inputs = inp,outputs = output_layer)
ANN.compile(optimizer=optimizers.SGD(learning_rate=0.1),loss="categorical_crossentropy",metrics=["accuracy"])

history = ANN.fit(train_data,validation_data=test_data,epochs=20)

Dropout technique works by randomly reducing the number of interconnecting neurons within a neural network. At every training step, each neuron has a chance of being left out, or rather, dropped out of the collated contribution from connected neurons. This technique minimizes overfitting because each neuron becomes independently sufficient, in the sense that the neurons within the layers learn weight values that are not based on the cooperation of its neighbouring neurons. Here is the implementation of the network with dropout for every layer.

In [12]:
train_data, test_data = data_reset(1/255.)


inp = layers.Input(shape=(80,80,1))
first_layer = layers.Flatten()(inp)
first_layer = layers.Dropout(0.1)(first_layer)
second_layer = layers.Dense(4096,activation="relu",kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.0001))(first_layer)
second_layer = layers.Dropout(0.1)(second_layer)
third_layer = layers.Dense(2048,activation="relu",kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.0001))(second_layer)
third_layer = layers.Dropout(0.1)(third_layer)
fourth_layer = layers.Dense(1024,activation="relu",kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.0001))(third_layer)
fourth_layer = layers.Dropout(0.1)(fourth_layer)
output_layer = layers.Dense(3,activation="softmax",kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.0001))(fourth_layer)

ANN = models.Model(inputs = inp,outputs = output_layer)
ANN.compile(optimizer=optimizers.SGD(learning_rate=0.1),loss="categorical_crossentropy",metrics=["accuracy"])

history = ANN.fit(train_data,validation_data=test_data,epochs=20)
